# swarm-plan.skill.src

## Intent
Decompose a design into a dispatch-ready work item tree of typed agents, using the
swarm decomposition protocol: a rigor-attenuation pass followed by five refinement
passes, sized to the cost of getting the work wrong.

## Carried

Everything that defines a correct decomposition is inlined below: the
decompose-by-outcome rule, Pass 0 rigor attenuation, the five passes with their
instructions and quality gates, the compaction / self-contained-item test, and the
canonical agent-type vocabulary the passes annotate against. This is the method,
lifted whole. The only things resolved locally are the binds in the next section:
which tracker creates items and wires dependencies, which agent specs actually
exist on this machine, and how this project routes a work domain to a specialist.

### The governing rule: decompose by outcome, never by implementation step

Each item is an outcome with a verifiable done condition, not an implementation
step. The done condition is a state of the world someone can check: what the user
sees, what the system does, what query returns what result. "Code exists" is never
a done condition.

Bad decomposition (implementation-scoped, forbidden):
- "Build the filtering layer"
- "Build the prompt construction"
- "Wire them together"

Good decomposition (outcome-scoped, required):
- "Baron's queue shows 5 relevant items when he opens the webapp"
- "Physical tasks don't appear in the agent work queue"
- "Staff manager mutations only reference open items"

Every item must be three things at once:
1. Outcome-defined: the done condition is a verifiable end state, not "code exists."
2. One-session-sized: completable in a single context window before compaction.
3. Self-contained: the description carries everything an agent with zero
   conversation history needs to execute it. Reasoning (why this approach),
   constraints (what NOT to do), failure modes already explored, and the exact
   done condition.

### Pass 0: Rigor Attenuation (always produces a dispatchable DAG)

Run this FIRST. Its job is to scale the DAG's rigor to the cost of getting the
work wrong, not to its apparent size, and not to refuse to plan. Pass 0 always
emits a dispatchable DAG. Rigor is the dial, the gate. A trivial task becomes a
single-implementer leaf; a heavy task becomes the full-rigor tree. The dispatcher
trusts whatever Pass 0 sized and does not re-litigate it at execution time.

Inputs: the user request, related work items, and a quick repo scan (file paths,
recent commits). Ask the user nothing unless genuinely ambiguous. Target: 30
seconds.

Compute three signals and one modifier. Take the max of the three signals, add the
modifier, clamp to the four tiers.

1. Blast radius (how much surface the work touches):
   - 1 file in 1 package: trivial
   - 2 to 5 files in 1 to 2 packages: small
   - 6+ files OR crossing core package boundaries: standard
   - more than 20 files OR spanning more than 3 packages: heavy

2. Reversibility cost (what it costs if the change is wrong):
   - Additive-only (add command X, add doc Y, new file Z): trivial
   - In-place mutation with no external contract (change behavior of Y): small
   - Interface, config, or CLI contract change: standard
   - Schema migration, public API change, on-disk format change: heavy

3. Adversarial surface (floors, not ceilings):
   - None of the below: trivial
   - Work-tracker state, a coordination protocol's internals, signing code, test-gate enforcement:
     standard floor
   - Auth, payment, secret handling, user data, anything security-labeled: heavy floor

4. Coverage modifier: if prod-code paths change and the touched path has no
   corresponding test coverage, add +1 tier. Applies at most once. Trivial can only
   bump to small.

Rigor tier = clamp(max(blast, reversibility, adversarial) + coverage_modifier,
trivial..heavy).

The tier controls how deep later passes go. The DAG is always dispatchable:

| Tier | Resulting DAG shape | Passes that apply |
|---|---|---|
| trivial | one implementer leaf; no review, no veracity, no sweeps | Pass 1, Pass 5 |
| small | implementer then reviewer (single review) | Pass 1, Pass 2, Pass 5 |
| standard | implementer then reviewer then veracity-adversary | Pass 1 through 3.5, Pass 5 |
| heavy | full rigor: implementers, reviewers, veracity, five sweeps, optional upstream adversarial design review | All passes |

Annotate the plan root with `rigor: <tier>`. Report the tier and the dominating
signal so the user can sanity-check ("blast=small, coverage bump, rigor: standard").
Then proceed to Pass 1 regardless. The user may override with an explicit rigor
tier; frequent overrides mean the signal set is mis-calibrated.

Worked examples:
- "add a new slash command in the CLI": blast=small, reversibility=trivial,
  adversarial=trivial, tier small. DAG = implementer + reviewer.
- "change a message signing envelope format": blast=small, reversibility=heavy,
  adversarial=heavy, tier heavy. Full rigor.
- "add a README paragraph": all trivial, tier trivial. One implementer.
- "refactor 14 detectors to share a base class": blast=standard, reversibility=small,
  adversarial=trivial, tier standard. Implementer + reviewer + veracity.
- "add a Polar checkout flow": blast=standard, reversibility=standard,
  adversarial=heavy, tier heavy. Full rigor.

### Canonical agent-type vocabulary

The passes annotate every item with one of these exact `agent-type` values.
Fragmented vocabulary (face vs face-card, e2e vs e2e-verification, veracity vs
veracity-adversary) breaks telemetry grouping, so use these spellings verbatim.
Which of these specs actually exist on the target is a BIND (see Bound). The
vocabulary itself is carried because the passes reference it.

| Canonical type | Use |
|---|---|
| implementer | Writes code, tests, commits |
| reviewer | Reviews implementation items |
| sweeper-security | Security-focused sweep |
| sweeper-bugs | Bug-focused sweep |
| sweeper-deadcode | Dead code sweep |
| sweeper-antipatterns | Antipattern sweep |
| sweeper-testcoverage | Test coverage sweep |
| veracity-adversary | Mock / test fidelity challenge |
| e2e-verification | End-to-end integration verification |

Project-specific types are allowed but must be hyphen-case.

### Pass 1: Outcome Mapping

Goal: the first-draft tree with correct outcomes and the lifecycle steps the tier
admits (implement, review, sweep, verify) encoded as typed items.

Apply only the construction steps your Pass 0 tier admits, per the tier table:
reviewers at rigor >= small, veracity-adversary at rigor >= standard, the five
sweeps and per-item security reviews only at heavy.

1. Read the design in full. Identify every distinct outcome (what the user sees,
   what the system does, what queries return what results).
2. Create one implementation item per outcome. The title states the outcome, the
   action.
3. Write each item description with: the done condition (a verifiable state of the
   world), the design reference, spec references (schemas, APIs, existing code the
   implementer needs), constraints (what NOT to do, scope boundaries), the agent
   type (`implementer`), and the artifact type (`code`, `spec`, `ops`, or `design`,
   classified by the primary artifact the done condition tests; default to `code`
   when ambiguous).
4. At rigor >= small, for each implementation item, create review child items, scaled
   by marginal yield. One reviewer is the minimum (a combined correctness + integration review).
   Two reviewers when the item touches a shared interface, security-adjacent code,
   or has high cascade risk (split into correctness and integration). Three or more
   only for unusual risk (novel architecture, cross-system integration, regulatory
   surfaces), justified in the description. Each review item depends on its
   implementation item.
5. At rigor >= standard, for each implementation wave, create a veracity audit item
   (`agent-type: veracity-adversary`). It runs in the same wave as the implementers,
   reading their tests as they are written. The wave cannot merge until veracity
   findings are resolved. This is concurrent adversarial pressure, a post-hoc
   review.
6. At heavy, for implementation items touching security-critical surfaces (authentication,
   authorization, crypto, invite/token flows, concurrent state mutation), create a
   security review child (`agent-type: sweeper-security`, opus) targeting TOCTOU
   races, auth bypass, data races under locks, audit-trail gaps. One per security
   surface, per implementation item.
7. At heavy, at the parent level, create the five sweep items, each depending on all
   implementation items completing: security (`sweeper-security`), bugs
   (`sweeper-bugs`), dead code (`sweeper-deadcode`), antipatterns
   (`sweeper-antipatterns`), test coverage (`sweeper-testcoverage`).
8. Create an end-to-end verification item only when the design spans 3+
   independently-built components that must work together, or the integration
   behavior cannot be verified by composing individual tests, or the design
   specifies user-facing workflows crossing service boundaries. When created, it
   depends on all implementation items.
9. Wire dependencies: sequential outcomes block each other; all children block the
   parent.
10. Status discipline: after wiring, only the parent and truly ready leaf items
    should appear in the tracker's ready queue. Do not pre-open blocked items; let
    the tracker auto-block them when deps are added. If more than ~5 items appear
    per parallel wave, the deps are wired wrong.

Quality gate: every item answers both "what does done look like?" and "who does
this work?" (agent type).

### Pass 2: Context Isolation and Parallelism

Goal: every item completable in one session, parallelism maximized.

1. Apply the compaction test to every item: if an agent reads this item cold, with
   zero conversation history, can it execute to completion? If not, the item is too
   large or missing context.
2. Split items that are too large. Signals: requires reading more than ~10 files to
   understand scope; has multiple independent done conditions (split one per
   condition); spans multiple unrelated subsystems; description exceeds ~500 words.
3. Make every description self-contained: file paths to read and modify, interface
   contracts (signatures, API shapes, schemas), and a mandatory test-depth
   annotation (one of `feature`, `bugfix`, `refactor`, `test-only`; `feature`
   requires integration tests, `bugfix` requires regression tests through the real
   pipeline, `refactor` requires existing integration tests pass, `test-only` means
   the item only adds or changes tests and those new tests exercise real, unmocked
   code paths). Never leave test-depth blank or write "unit tests."
4. Maximize parallelism: find items that are sequentially ordered but actually
   independent; factor out shared prerequisites as their own items.
5. Annotate each item with an estimated model tier (haiku/sonnet/opus).

Quality gate: no item requires another item's implementation details, only its
interface contract.

### Pass 3: Standards Enforcement (applies at rigor >= standard)

At trivial and small, skip. The one- or two-leaf DAG takes its standards from the
implementer and reviewer specs directly.

1. TDD: every implementation item specifies the test-first sequence (write the
   failing test that defines the done condition, implement to pass, run scoped
   verification green). If the done condition is not expressible as a test, flag it.
2. SRP: each item produces one coherent change. If a description says "and also,"
   it is two items.
3. SOLID: descriptions must not prescribe implementations that violate
   open/closed, Liskov, interface segregation, or dependency inversion.
4. YAGNI: strip anything anticipating future requirements. If it is in the
   design, it is in the item.
5. Project conventions: reference existing patterns (naming, file organization,
   error handling, logging).
6. Enforcement mechanisms bundle their proof. Any item implementing a gate, guard,
   validator, or quality floor MUST include both the test proving the gate rejects
   bad input and the test proving it passes good input, written by the same
   implementer in the same dispatch. Do not split enforcement implementation from
   enforcement testing.

Quality gate: read each item as an agent would. Does it tell you to write a test
first, and to avoid over-engineering?

### Pass 3.5: Veracity Challenge (applies at rigor >= standard; opus)

At trivial and small, skip (no veracity-adversary leaf to feed). At heavy,
mandatory.

1. For every implementation item, ask: what would a sonnet-tier implementer mock to
   close this fast? The answer is almost always the external integration, the
   database, the API call, the service boundary.
2. Rewrite the done condition so mocking is impossible. "test hits Polar sandbox,
   sends real payment, receives real webhook, verifies subscription state in
   database," "test covers checkout flow."
3. Identify what real testing needs (credentials, sandbox accounts, running
   services). Create prerequisite items for anything a human must provision before
   the implementation wave.
4. Where real testing needs something the agent cannot provision, the prerequisite
   item is itself the deliverable and goes to the human first.
5. If a done condition cannot be expressed as a ground-source-truth test, flag it.
   Untestable features do not ship.

Quality gate: for every implementation item, the done condition specifies what the
test must actually hit. No done condition is satisfiable by mocking the primary
interface under test.

### Pass 4: System Validation (opus; the most valuable pass, never downgrade)

1. Coverage check: walk every design requirement, identify which item(s) deliver
   it; if a requirement has no item, create it.
2. Hallucination check: walk every item; if it serves no design requirement,
   remove or flag it.
3. Interface consistency: producers and consumers of an interface agree on the
   contract.
4. Dependency integrity: no circular, missing, or phantom deps.
5. Integration surface: every point where independently-built items integrate has a
   review or verification item covering it.
6. Mock blast radius: for each item changing an interface, enumerate every test file
   that mocks it; record as a `mock-scope` annotation so implementers update those
   mocks alongside their source.
7. Agent-type validation: each item's assigned agent type matches the work.

Quality gate: every design requirement maps to at least one item; every item maps
to at least one design requirement; every item has the correct agent type.

### Pass 5: Dispatch Readiness

1. Cold-start simulation: for each item, assume the agent has no context. Can it
   complete from the description alone?
2. Agent-type matching: introspect the local agent registry (BIND). For each item's
   agent type, verify a matching spec exists. If not, map to the closest available
   agent, fall back to the standard set, or flag for the user when no reasonable
   match exists.
3. Model tier assignment: implementer = sonnet (opus for complex architecture),
   reviewer = sonnet, sweeper = sonnet, designer/veracity-planning = opus.
4. Failure cascade analysis: items whose failure blocks the most downstream work are
   high-priority; consider a higher tier.
5. Dispatch summary: each item annotated with agent type, model tier, and key
   dependencies.

Quality gate: for every item, the orchestrator knows what agent to spawn, what
model to use, and what the item depends on.

### Presentation discipline

After the passes, present a top-level summary only. Do not dump the full DAG.

```
Parent: <item-id>: <title>
Children:
  <item-id>: <title> [agent-type, model-tier]
  ...

Total items: N
By agent type: implementer xN, reviewer xN, sweeper xN
Critical path: N items (~N waves)
Full DAG: <tracker dep-tree command> <parent-id>
```

Then STOP. The user reviews and approves before any dispatch. If the user points at
a pass as needing rework, re-run from that pass forward (structural to Pass 1,
sizing to Pass 2, standards to Pass 3, coverage to Pass 4, dispatch to Pass 5).

## Bound

bind:tracker
  requires: a work-item tracker on this machine that can create items, create child
  items under a parent, add a dependency edge between two items, show the ready
  queue, and render a dependency tree. Resolve to its concrete create / child /
  dep-add / ready / dep-tree command forms. Used by every pass that creates or
  wires items, and by the presentation summary.

bind:agent-registry
  requires: the local directory of typed-agent specs (where this harness keeps its
  per-project agent definitions). Pass 5 introspects it to confirm a spec exists for
  each `agent-type` an item names. If the project has no local registry, resolve to
  the machine's standard agent set as the fallback source.

bind:routing-table
  requires: this project's domain-to-agent routing map (which work domain dispatches
  to which specialist agent type). Used in Pass 1 and Pass 4 to assign and validate
  each item's `agent-type`. Resolve to the project's documented routing (typically
  in CLAUDE.md) or, absent one, to the canonical vocabulary above mapped by work
  kind (implementation to implementer, review to reviewer, sweep to sweeper-*, mock
  challenge to veracity-adversary).

## Checks
- (mechanical) Every item in the produced tree has an `agent-type` annotation, and
  every value is one of the canonical vocabulary spellings (or a hyphen-case
  project type). No bare words, snake_case, or fragmented spellings.
- (mechanical) Every `agent-type` named in the tree has a resolvable spec in the
  bound agent registry (or the documented fallback). Pass 5 fails loud otherwise.
- (mechanical) The plan root carries a `rigor: <tier>` annotation from Pass 0, one
  of trivial/small/standard/heavy, and the tree shape matches the tier table
  (trivial = one implementer leaf; small adds a reviewer; standard adds veracity;
  heavy adds the five sweeps).
- (mechanical) After wiring, the tracker's ready queue shows only the parent and
  genuinely actionable leaves, not the whole tree (≤ ~5 per parallel wave).
- (behavioral) Every item is an outcome with a verifiable done condition (a state
  of the world), an implementation step. No item title is a build-X action and no
  done condition is "code exists."
- (behavioral) Every item passes the compaction test: an agent with zero
  conversation history can execute it from the description alone (paths, contracts,
  constraints, done condition, test-depth all present).
- (behavioral) Rigor is attenuated to the cost of getting the work wrong: the
  reported tier follows from the three signals + coverage modifier, and a trivial
  request did not produce a full-rigor tree (nor a heavy request a bare leaf).
- (behavioral) At rigor >= standard, every implementation item's done condition
  specifies what the test must actually hit; none is satisfiable by mocking the
  primary interface under test.
